segments.text: I didn't go to A&M, I went to Texas Lutheran instead.
Oh, you didn't go?
I thought you were probably an ex.

Okay, first of all, Mr. Coon, would you tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, if you know them, where they were born, where you were born, the schools you attended before you came to Texas A&M.
My father's name was Victor A. Kuhn and my mother's name was Beulah Riggs Kuhn and my father was born February 29th 1872 and he died March 27th 1926.
My mother was born
August 25, 1877, and she died November 16, 1966.
I'm not certain which county my father was born in, but I think it's probably in Victoria County.
At any rate, he was born in Texas, either Victoria or Lavaca County.
And my mother, I'm quite sure, was born in Lavaca County, Texas.
What else?
You were born when and where?
I was born near Runge, Texas.
That's in Carnes County.
August 14, 1899.
And did you go to school in Runge?
I went to Runge public school and high school.
What factors were involved in your choice of Texas A&M as your school or college?
Well, I had heard a good deal about the school and the life there, the type of, the fact that it was a boys' school and living in dormitories.
Had there been some other boys from Rooney who went there that you talked to?
Yes, there was one that went a year or two, several years before I did, Preston Tom.
I think he went there a year or two.
But I never had discussed it with him.
But what you had heard led you to believe that it would be a pretty good place to go.
Yes, that's true.
Were there any special procedures you had to go through to
to be admitted to the school?
I don't recall it.
Our school grad certificate of graduation, I think, was all I recall.
Did you just appear on the scene in time for registration and were accepted then?
That's correct.
You didn't have to go through the application and acceptance procedure that's in existence now?
No, sir.
No, sir.
What was your first reaction to the school and to College Station when you arrived there?
And you might tell us also how you got there.
Well, I got there by train, of course.
That's about the only way you could
get around in those days.
Oh, my reaction was, I guess, about like any other country boy.
I never had been anyplace except Rung End.
It was new to me.
Wasn't any kind of reception committee there to meet you?
No, I didn't.
To be aware, I didn't see them.
OK.
How did you get your material that you brought with you from the train station to wherever you were going to stay?
And how were you assigned a place to stay the first night, if you recall?
I don't recall how we were assigned.
I know where I was assigned to, but I don't remember in what way, and I don't remember how I got my trunk.
Well, at one point there was an old Negro man by the name of Uncle Dan who had a team of white mules that he carried baggage from the train to the... Could have been, but I don't recall it.
Did you stay your first night in the dormitory that you stayed for the whole first year?
Yes, as far as I can recall, yes, I think so.
Would you describe, say, a typical day during your four years there?
What time did you get up, and how did you wake up, and what hours did you spend in class, and what hours did you spend doing other things, and then what did you do about going to bed?
Well, I, of course, can't remember exactly the hour, but we got up
At that time, of course, everybody was in the cadet corps.
And we got up by the sound of Reveille and we had a few minutes to get out and go through some calisthenics, the first thing we did.
And of course we went back and got the rest of our uniform on.
Pretty soon we went to breakfast and we marched to all the meals lined up along Military Walk.
And in the evening or noon, I've forgotten, one time a day at least, we marched by band music to Mess Hall, which was down at the end of Military Walk, Sopisa Hall, I don't know what it was called.
You want to know what?
Just approximately how many hours you spent in class in a given day.
I don't remember that for sure.
I'd say probably about four.
And I would say, what, most of those would be in the morning and in the afternoon?
Yes, and then in the afternoon we'd have

laboratory work and some time and we might have had some classes in the afternoon but I don't recall for sure uh what about drill we had drill several times a week as I remembered but I don't remember how many times out on the drill field close order drill
That's out in the field that's now in front of the MSC?
Yes, that's right.
And what time did you go to bed then?
Well, they would blow taps for us to go to bed, and best I recall is somewhere around 10 o'clock, possibly 10.30, I don't remember for sure.
What was...
lifelike in the dormitory.
Well, once in a while we'd, I was in the basement of Milner Hall, the freshmen, most of the freshmen were in the basement, not all of them.
I was in eye company and we had a half of the basement of Milner Hall and
K Company had the other half.
And all the various things would happen, like sometime during the night they'd throw sacks of water in on your bed.
That's one thing I can remember.
I don't remember specifically.
Milner Hall was what fairly new at the time.
Yeah it was fairly new.
It was located as you probably know down near the mess hall.
How many to a room?
Two.
And then what both fish?
During your freshman year you were both of you in the room were freshmen?
Yes my cousin who was actually my foster brother went
with me the first year, and we roomed together.
Okay.
You mentioned that you lived in Millner your freshman year.
Do you remember what other dormitories you lived in?
Yes, my sophomore and junior year I lived in Leggett Hall, and senior year I was in Buzell.
That was new.

That was a new building that year and they at that time decided on a policy of trying to separate the sophomores from the freshmen other than those who were corporals in the company and so they organized two companies of sophomores and I had one of them, a fellow named George
captain of the other sophomore company.
Now, this was which year?
My senior year.
Your senior year.
Yes.
OK. And for that reason, I don't know very many of the fellows that were freshmen the year that I finished, because there weren't any freshmen.
Well, you had only sophomores in your company.
OK.
I noticed you switched from I Company to D Company.
D Second.
D Second.
That was because the enrollment increased to the point where they had to form another regiment.
And that caused it.
And after two years in D Company, then you switched to E Company.
Yes.
I did that because that's where they...
point it made me captain.
Was that a fairly common practice, what I was saying, is taking somebody who had been a sergeant in one company and making them a captain in another company?
No, I don't believe it was too common.
I think one thing it explained at that year is the fact that, like I said, it was the first time they'd had sophomore segregation, you might say, from freshmen.

In fact, another thing was the enrollment that year had fallen off due to the war and just a few of us that were in the officer's training camp who were in the service at all that were able to get back and go to school that year.
They let us start
in January and run a little bit late, so we were not in school, a good many of us, that fall.
That would be the fall of 1918.
Right.
Okay.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Well, I didn't have any complaint about it.
Enjoyed it.
Well, I've talked to a number of people who said they gained a good bit of weight.
Well, yes.
I don't know whether that was altogether due to the food.
Part of it might have been the regular hours that you had to keep.
Both of them, I think.
But I imagine you also got a fair amount of physical exercise to counterbalance the food.
Yes.
Our drill was enough for that.
I can't remember just how many times a week we did it but several times.
Was there a pretty good variety of food or was it pretty much the same each week?
Well, I don't recall it being too much the same but I really don't have a clear recollection.
very bad, or I think I'd remember it.
I think it must have been pretty satisfactory.
What privileges did the upperclassmen have that freshmen did not enjoy?
Well, freshmen didn't enjoy any to speak of.
As I remember it, we were allowed to go to Bryan on Saturday afternoon, and I think we had to be back for supper.
As far as I can recall, that's the only privilege that we had.
If we had any others, I can't recall.
Okay, but what did upperclassmen have then?
Well, they could go a little more often, but I don't remember just how much.
Go a little more often and stay a little longer sometimes?
Stay a little longer, yes, sir, but I don't remember the particulars about that.
What kind of duties did the freshmen have to perform for the upperclassmen?
Oh, I can't recall the duties, but then every once in a while I'd have a little, you'd bend it on you, you know, this hazing procedure.
I can't recall them.
That's it.
If you didn't do something the way they wanted you to or something?
Well, no, I don't think it was for any particular reason.
It was just to let you know that you were a freshman, I think.
I don't recall it.
Well, a couple of people told me that they ran all kinds of errands and made beds.
I don't recall doing that.
I'm sure some of that was done, but I don't remember doing that.
Was there any way that, say, a visitor to the campus could distinguish the various classes from each other?
Say, how could you identify a freshman?
Or was there a way?
I don't recall there was any way to distinguish the classes other than that, to this extent,

All the corporals at that time were out of the sophomore class, and all the sergeants and first sergeants and so on were junior class, and all the commissioned officers, lieutenant and captain, major and colonel were senior class.
If they didn't, if there were not a, if a private way, I don't recall if there was any way you could tell the difference.
But were there a pretty substantial number who remained private the whole four years they were there?
There were a few senior privates when I was there, yeah.
Not many.
Do you have any idea why they never attained a higher rank?
Well, I assume because they weren't particularly interested in the military part of it.
At that time, though, they did have to wear a uniform and attend drill.
But I would imagine, though, since all corporals came from the sophomore class, if you didn't make corporal as a sophomore, you didn't have much chance of going up the rank.
Well, I didn't make it as a sophomore.
When I was through luck, I suppose, I was the first sergeant.
So you skipped the rank of corporal, then.
You went private to sergeant.
That's right.
Well, it was the increase in enrollment that made two regiments, which kind of doubled the number of officers you had to have.
Yeah, and then in my senior year, the enrollment had dropped some on account of the war.
What did the students do for entertainment and recreation?
I mean, how'd they occupy their time when they weren't in class or drilling or anything of that nature?
Did you?
Well, one thing we'd sometimes do for recreation, there was what they called a fish pond about, I suppose it was a couple of miles
I guess it would be west.
It was a pretty good-sized pond of water, and we'd go out there swimming.
This would have been then probably across the railroad tracks from the school.
Yes, it was in the direction of the railroad station on out.
I believe that would have been to the west, the best I remember.
At one point, this was probably later, I guess, because there was a pond out there that was part of the sewage treatment plant, I think, that Mr. Giesecke had designed.
Do you know where Eastwood Airport is?
No, I don't.
Okay.
All right.
Well, I don't imagine it's the same thing, because you wouldn't have been swimming in that unless they had...
the lake and later converted it to part of their sewage treatment.
Well that's possible.
Were there any things besides swimming did you have anything to do at the YMCA?
No I never did.
I don't know I don't remember whether there was any recreation
There was a YMCA there at the time, but I don't remember whether it was any recreation.
At one point, there was a swimming pool in the basement of the YMCA.
If there was when I was there, I don't remember.
Did you participate in any of the intramural athletics?
Oh, I played just a little bit of baseball, but very little.
I wasn't too hot.
Were there a pretty substantial percentage of the fellows who played baseball?
any intramural sports?
Yes, I think a big percent of them did.
I gather it was a fairly competitive, highly competitive sort of thing, was it not?
Yes, it was.
I say that because I've seen in some of the annuals where people have been listed, they were part of the
championship basketball team, so it seems to have been somewhat of an honor to have been on the championship team.
Did you have any favorite teachers while you were there?
If you can remember who they were and why you liked them.
We're getting back too far.
I can't recall any in particular.
Okay.
I was wondering, a couple of the people I've talked to, I noticed you were in chemical engineering.
Well, I was like Dr. Hedges, who was the head of the

department at the time quite well but he didn't actually teach me he was primarily administration that's correct now what I was getting at in chemical engineering did you take a fair amount of chemistry courses in addition to that a couple people that I've talked to have not been particularly fond of the chemistry department because I think that was kind of the average attitude of most of them
A goodly number of people busted freshman chemistry.
Yes, that's true.
Must have been a pretty tough one.
What was the attitude of the students toward the administration?
And I guess there would really be, as I understand it, a dual administration role.
One, the president's office that sort of handled the education end, and the commandant's office that did the military end.
That's true.
Well, as far as I know, the attitude of the students was good.
I don't recall any... Do you ever have any contact with, I believe, Dr. Bezell?
Yes, he was president at the time.
Was he fairly open to the students?
I mean, if you had a problem, could you go see him about it?
Well, I suppose that you could.
I never did, but I assume that you could.
I don't...
I didn't have any occasions.
One of the things that is of interest to us at present time is the number of the traditions and customs that exist at Texas A&M.
And we have some difficulty pinpointing when things started and things of that nature.
Can you remember anything new that was started while you were there?
No, sir, I don't believe I can recall anything.
Did you have a campus muster on April 21st?
I can't recall that we did.
We used to have Yale practice, I know, for... For ball games?
Ball games, yeah.
Midnight Yale practices, sir.
Well, no, they were long in the evening.
After supper sometime.
Between supper and the quiet study hour.
Study hour, yeah.
Were there any girls in any of the classes you attended?
I ask that because we know that at various and sundry times there were a few girls.
I was thinking there might have been... Because this is the whole thing.
The people in the cities...

I'm not sure whether they were in my classes, but I think I can recall there were one or two girls that they were either daughters of professors or lived at Bryan, something like that, but there were very few.
I don't recall for sure whether there was any in one of my classes, but I believe there were two or three there in the school at that time.
Earlier, when we were talking about entertainment, about privileges, you mentioned about going to Bryan.
Yes.
Was that on the, what was it called, the Tunerville Trolley?
Yeah, that was an interurban car that ran by.
What, for what purposes did the students go to Bryan?
Oh, just to, not anything in particular, just to
go to town.
There was, I take it then, really nothing as far as the town of College Station was concerned.
No stores, at least very few.
There were a few out on the fringes there, but not many.
Sort of in that area behind Speza?
I believe, yes, yeah.
So it was just a matter of getting off the campus for a little while.
That was about all there was to it, the best I remember.
We know that a substantial percentage of the boys who went to A&M worked part-time while they were there.
Did you have any time of employment?
I did.
In my freshman year, I worked as a janitor some.
But after that, I didn't work anymore.
About how much time did you put in working?
Oh, maybe uh...
I don't remember for sure.
Maybe an hour a day or... How much did you get an hour?
Do you remember?
No, I don't have any recollection of that.
Seems like for a good long while the standard wages I believe were 25 cents an hour.
Well, I wouldn't be surprised.
I know at that time wages in general were not very high.
Did the students who participated in regular intercollegiate athletics, like football, basketball, and baseball, have any privileges that the other students didn't have?
You mean intramural?
No, I mean who played on the college team.
Yes, I think they did.
I know they had a training table.
They ate at a...
what they call a training table together, you know.
Well, it was on the football squad, and I don't remember for certain about the other sports, but I think possibly so, but I know the football, being made together.
But did they stay with their regular company then?
Best I can remember, yes.
I think then each dormitory was sort of assigned to companies.
That's right.
Depending upon the size, there'd be one or more companies in a dormitory.
That's true.
That's right.
Earlier you mentioned that part of what was your senior year, the fall of 1918,
You were not on campus, actually.
You were in Officer's Training School.
Where was that?
That was near Waco, Camp MacArthur.
I don't think it's in existence any longer.
Okay, so...
It was just a tent.
We lived in tents.
Did you go there immediately after the end of your junior year?
No.
We first went...
for a month at Fort Sheridan in the ROTC program.
That's in Illinois.
That would have been in June?
Yes, in June.
And then while we were there, about the time that month was up, they offered us a two-month enlistment for an additional

a training camp at that same location other than the ROTC camp and some of us stayed and some of them got commissions from that but I did not and I went on back at the end of that two months to school and we enlisted there in the what was then called the SATC and I stayed there at school
possibly a week, and we were then, most of us, sent to camp back out there.
And this SATC stood for what?
Student Army Training Corps, I believe.
